I - Pratical problem

Predict if a person involved in a road accident is heavily injured or dead using the caracteristics of the accidents.

The dataset comes from the French government database (https://www.data.gouv.fr/fr/datasets/base-de-donnees-accidents-corporels-de-la-circulation) For the purpose of our project, we will focus only on July 2018 accidents.

II - Mathematical problem

The problem is to explain the Y variable (binary variable stating if the person involved in the accident is injured/dead or not) by the other variables.

\[Y=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{if the person involved is hospitalised or dead} \\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{array}\right.\]

\[col=\text{type of collision}\quad col=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{two vehicles frontal} \\ 2 & \text{two vehicles from behind } \\ 3 & \text{two vehicles from the side} \\ 4 & \text{three vehicles or more - in a row} \\ 5 & \text{three vehicles or more -multiple collision } \\ 6 & \text{other collision } \\ 7 & \text{without collision} \end{array}\right.\]

\[int=\text{type of intersection}\quad int=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{off intersection} \\ 2 & \text{X intersection } \\ 3 & \text{T intersection} \\ 4 & \text{Y intersection} \\ 5 & \text{Intersection with more than 4 roads } \\ 6 & \text{oroundabout} \\ 7 & \text{square} \\ 8 & \text{railroad crossing} \\ 9 & \text{other intersection} \end{array}\right.\]

\[atm=\text{atmospheric conditions}\quad atm=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{normal} \\ 2 & \text{light rain } \\ 3 & \text{heavy rain} \\ 4 & \text{snow} \\ 5 & \text{fog} \\ 6 & \text{heavy wind} \\ 7 & \text{very sunny} \\ 8 & \text{cloudy weather} \\ 9 & \text{other} \end{array}\right.\]

\[catr=\text{road category}\quad catr=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{Highway} \\ 2 & \text{national road } \\ 3 & \text{departmental road} \\ 4 & \text{communal road} \\ 5 & \text{outside public track} \\ 6 & \text{parking lot} \\ 9 & \text{other} \\ \end{array}\right.\]

\[catv2=\text{vehicle category}\quad catv2=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{light vehicle} \\ 2 & \text{truck } \\ 3 & \text{scooter} \\ 4 & \text{bike} \\ 5 & \text{other} \\ \end{array}\right.\]

\[choc=\text{initial impact position}\quad choc=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{front} \\ 2 & \text{front-right} \\ 3 & \text{front-left} \\ 4 & \text{back} \\ 5 & \text{back-right} \\ 6 & \text{back-left} \\ 7 & \text{right side} \\ 8 & \text{left side} \\ 9 & \text{multiple impacts} \end{array}\right.\]

\[sexe=\text{sex of the user}\quad sexe=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{male} \\ 2 & \text{female} \\ \end{array}\right.\]

\[age=\text{age of the user}\] \[hour-period=\text{Time of the accident}\quad hour-period=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{Between 0:00 and 4:00 Am} \\ 2 & \text{Between 4:00 and 8:00 Am} \\ 3 & \text{Between 8:00 and 12:00 Am} \\ 4 & \text{Between 12:00 and 16:00 Pm} \\ 5 & \text{Between 16:00 and 20:00 Pm} \\ 6 & \text{Between 20:00 and 24:00 Pm} \\ \end{array}\right.\]

\[day-number=\text{Day of the accident}\quad day-number=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{Monday} \\ 2 & \text{Tuesday} \\ 3 & \text{Wednesday} \\ 4 & \text{Thursday} \\ 5 & \text{Friday} \\ 6 & \text{Saturday} \\ 7 & \text{Sunday} \\ \end{array}\right.\]

\[place=\text{seat number}\quad driver=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{driver} \\ 2:9 & \text{passenger} \\ \end{array}\right.\]

III - Database Creation and Clean-up.

#data import
caracteristiques=read.csv('caracteristiques-2018.csv',na.strings=c('NA',''))
lieux=read.csv('lieux-2018.csv',na.strings=c('NA',''))
usagers=read.csv('usagers-2018.csv',na.strings=c('NA',''))
vehicules=read.csv('vehicules-2018.csv',na.strings=c('NA',''))

#merging data
data1=left_join(caracteristiques,lieux,by=c('Num_Acc'='Num_Acc'))
data2=left_join(usagers,vehicules,by=c('Num_Acc'='Num_Acc','num_veh'='num_veh'))
data=left_join(data2,data1,by=c('Num_Acc'='Num_Acc'))


#filter on mainland france
data = data %>% filter(dep < 970) #exclusion territoire d'outre mer


#create the output variable : if user hospitalized or dead = 1, else = 0
data = data %>% mutate(Y = ifelse(between(grav,2,3),1,0)) %>% select(-grav)


#create age column
data = data %>% mutate(age=2018-an_nais) %>% select(-an_nais)

#transform hour into a period
data=data %>% mutate(hour_period=ifelse(between(hrmn,0,399),1,
                                   ifelse(between(hrmn,400,799),2,
                                            ifelse(between(hrmn,800,1199),3,
                                               ifelse(between(hrmn,1200,1599),4,
                                                  ifelse(between(hrmn,1600,1999),5,
                                                      ifelse(between(hrmn,2000,2399),6,0))))))) %>% select(-hrmn)

#create day of the week number columns and filtering on July
data = data %>% 
  mutate(jour = ifelse(nchar(jour)==1,paste("0",jour,sep=""),jour),
         mois = ifelse(nchar(mois)==1,paste("0",mois,sep=""),mois)) %>%
  unite("date",c(jour,mois,an),sep="/")

data = data %>%  
  mutate(date = as.Date(date,format = "%d/%m/%y"),
         day_number = strftime(data$date,format = '%u'),
         month_number = strftime(data$date,format = '%m')) %>%
  filter(month_number=="07") %>%
  select(-date)
  
  
#synthesize car category 
data = data %>% mutate(catv2 = ifelse(catv == 7,1,
                                      ifelse(between(catv,13,15),2,
                                             ifelse(catv %in% c(2,5,4,31,32,33,34),3,
                                                    ifelse(catv == 1,4,5))))) %>%
  select(-catv)

#select only relevant columns
data = data %>% select(Y,col,int,atm,catr,catv2,choc,sexe,age,hour_period,day_number,place,dep,lat,long)
  
#make categorical variables
data$sexe=as.factor(data$sexe)
data$catv2=as.factor(data$catv2)
data$choc=as.factor(data$choc)
data$int=as.factor(data$int)
data$atm=as.factor(data$atm)
data$col=as.factor(data$col)
data$catr=as.factor(data$catr)
data$hour_period=as.factor(data$hour_period)
data$day_number=as.factor(data$day_number)
data$place = as.factor(data$place)

Logistic model with all the variables

We perform a logistic model on a train dataset with the following split:
- a training set of 70% of the data
- a test set of 30%.

There are many variables significant, conditioned on the intercept.

The intercept is made of : two vehicules in a frontal collision on a highway, off intersetion, with normal atmospheric conditions, with a light vehicle, with an initial impact on the front, with a Male user driving between 0 and 4am on Monday.

It is hard to interpret clearly the coefficient because of the high dimension. For the analysis of coefficients, we have to assume each time that only one coefficient changes and all other intercept coefficients remain equal.

However we can conclude that :
- the age of the driver is very significant
- the day of the week is not helpful to say if an accident has more chance to be fatal
- atmospheric conditions neither
- intersection type neither
- the frontal collision type is the most likely to be fatal (as coefficients of col2, col3, col4, col5 are negative and significant)
- an accident with a scooter or a bike has more chance to be fatal

VI - Machine Learning

We make a 10-K cross validation, training and testing 10 times five different methods : Ridge, Lasso, Random Forest, Full logistic model, Backward logistic model.

set.seed(1234)

data_ML_X = model.matrix(Y~.,data=data_ML)[,-1]
data_ML_Y = as.numeric(data_ML[,'Y'])


folds <- createFolds(1:nrow(data_ML),k=10,returnTrain = FALSE)
prev_AUC = matrix(0,nrow=nrow(data_ML),ncol=5) %>% as.data.frame()
prev_Error = matrix(0,nrow=nrow(data_ML),ncol=5) %>% as.data.frame()
names(prev_AUC) = c('ridge','lasso','forest','full','back')
names(prev_Error) = c('ridge','lasso','forest','full','back')

for (k in 1:10){
  train.X = data_ML_X[-folds[[k]],]
  test.X = data_ML_X[folds[[k]],]
  train.Y = data_ML_Y[-folds[[k]]]
  
  train = data_ML %>% slice(-folds[[k]])
  test = data_ML %>% slice(folds[[k]])
  
  ridge.cv = cv.glmnet(train.X,train.Y,alpha = 0,family="binomial",lambda = exp(seq(-8,4,length=100)))
  lasso.cv = cv.glmnet(train.X,train.Y,alpha = 1,family="binomial",lambda = exp(seq(-8,4,length=100)))
  forest.cv = ranger(Y~.,data=train,probability = TRUE)
  full.logit <- glm(Y~.,data=train,family="binomial")
  mod.back <- step(full.logit,direction="backward",k=log(nrow(train)),trace=0)
  
  prev_AUC[folds[[k]],1] = as.vector(predict(ridge.cv,newx=test.X,type='response'))
  prev_AUC[folds[[k]],2] = as.vector(predict(lasso.cv,newx=test.X,type='response'))
  prev_AUC[folds[[k]],3] = predict(forest.cv,data = test)[1]$predictions[,2]
  prev_AUC[folds[[k]],4] = predict(full.logit,newdata=test,type="response")
  prev_AUC[folds[[k]],5] = predict(mod.back,newdata=test,type="response") 

  prev_Error[folds[[k]],1] = predict(ridge.cv,newx=test.X,type='class',s="lambda.min")
  prev_Error[folds[[k]],2] = predict(lasso.cv,newx=test.X,type='class',s="lambda.min")
}

We make a comparison of the 5 methods with ROC curve and AUC (estimated on the test dataset).

result_AUC = data.frame(prev_AUC,data_ML_Y)
prev1 = result_AUC %>% gather(key = "Method", value ="score",-data_ML_Y) 

prev1 %>% group_by(Method) %>% summarize(AUC = auc(data_ML_Y,score)) %>% arrange(desc(AUC))

We make a comparison of the 5 methods with the error probability (estimated on the test dataset).

The risk is estimated with the test set according to

\[\frac{1}{n_{test}}\sum_{i\in test}(Y_i-\widehat m(X_i))^2.\]

prev_Error[,3] = prev_Error[,3] %>% round() %>% as.factor()
prev_Error[,4] = prev_Error[,4] %>% round() %>% as.factor()
prev_Error[,5] = prev_Error[,5] %>% round() %>% as.factor()

prev = data.frame(prev_Error, data_ML_Y)

prev %>% summarise_at(vars(1:5),~(mean((.!=data_ML_Y)^2)))
